WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:07.320
So we're going to switch to ADCs and myeloma. And I stole this slide from Amrita from a discussion

00:00:07.320 --> 00:00:13.280
we had last night, really looking at the recent advancements in immunotherapy and myeloma in the

00:00:13.280 --> 00:00:21.040
timeline. And you can see it's a crowded space. And so a BCMA ADC, so if it's where, like where

00:00:21.040 --> 00:00:26.320
should we be putting this drug? I will point to the left side of the slide and say that

00:00:26.320 --> 00:00:34.060
belantamab was our first approved BCMA therapy in myeloma in 2020, right? And so we had actually

00:00:34.060 --> 00:00:39.460
a lot of patients on belantamab back in the day, and now it's kind of fallen off the spectrum. But

00:00:39.460 --> 00:00:44.080
let me see if I can actually bring it back in a little bit. Now, so I was thinking about this

00:00:44.080 --> 00:00:49.820
last night and, you know, what is my algorithm? What's my BCMA algorithm? What should an algorithm

00:00:49.820 --> 00:00:55.740
be for any one of the centers? And so the premise of the algorithm in my mind,

00:00:56.320 --> 00:01:01.440
and this is, you know, the world according to Tom Martin, that you hopefully at UCSF,

00:01:01.520 --> 00:01:06.760
my colleagues agree, but everyone should get a BCMA treatment. There's no doubt about it. These

00:01:06.760 --> 00:01:13.100
are the most potent drugs. But for me, the default order is, can they get a CAR? If not, can they get

00:01:13.100 --> 00:01:19.820
a bispecific? If not, then can they get belantamab? And that's my default order. So if it's somebody

00:01:19.820 --> 00:01:24.640
that's BCMA exposed and it's a no, the first thing, the first question to that patient is,

00:01:24.820 --> 00:01:26.000
can you do a CAR?

00:01:26.320 --> 00:01:30.880
Can you put together all the, you know, what you need together? Can you put together a caregiver?

00:01:31.180 --> 00:01:34.640
Can you get to the center? Can you stay in San Francisco for a month? And if so,

00:01:34.900 --> 00:01:41.460
that person's a CAR candidate and we're going to proceed to CAR right away. If not, then the next

00:01:41.460 --> 00:01:45.680
discussion is, are they a bispecific candidate? They still need a caregiver and they still need

00:01:45.680 --> 00:01:50.460
to be able to do a lot of the driving into the academic center at the current time. Hopefully

00:01:50.460 --> 00:01:55.200
that'll get better. And if they can't do that, then I think for sure, then we have to consider

00:01:56.320 --> 00:02:03.000
the next, you know, therapy for them. Now over to the right side of the slide, I do think that in

00:02:03.000 --> 00:02:10.340
fact, some of these therapies are, have patients that overlap. Some patients can do a CAR, some

00:02:10.340 --> 00:02:15.020
patients can do a bispecific and the same patient can potentially do a BCMA. So then you have to

00:02:15.020 --> 00:02:20.900
make a choice. But I also think there's people that there are CAR candidates that they can do

00:02:20.900 --> 00:02:24.960
CAR and they should get CAR, but there are many people that can't and they'll never get a CAR.

00:02:25.160 --> 00:02:26.300
And so you shouldn't even be thinking about that. So I think that's a good idea.

00:02:26.300 --> 00:02:32.680
So then you think, is it bispecific or is it ADC? And there's other patients that, you know,

00:02:32.740 --> 00:02:39.520
maybe they can get a BCMA bispecific and sure, you're going to give them a bispecific, but there's

00:02:39.520 --> 00:02:44.280
also people that in fact, can't do that for many reasons, including where, you know, where they

00:02:44.280 --> 00:02:50.320
live. Some people, I was on a call with Doug Sporoff yesterday and he's like, when I have

00:02:50.320 --> 00:02:56.200
somebody way out in Montana, how am I going to give them these therapies? You can always give

00:02:56.280 --> 00:03:03.960
it. So what do I think in the bottom? Bella candidates, older, maybe they have less access

00:03:03.960 --> 00:03:09.980
to the academic center. This is really important that there's infrequent dosing. They may need to

00:03:09.980 --> 00:03:15.480
come and get a dose every three or four months, which, which would be great actually. What we

00:03:15.480 --> 00:03:21.760
really need to see if Bella will come back into mainstream is we need data on Bella after CAR

00:03:21.760 --> 00:03:26.260
and bispecific. Does it, do patients respond after they've received another BCMA bispecific?

00:03:26.260 --> 00:03:31.280
And that's really, I think quite important. All right. Now I'm going to give in the next three

00:03:31.280 --> 00:03:35.980
minutes, some of the, of the obligatory slides on responses, et cetera. Okay. Here we go.

00:03:36.540 --> 00:03:43.600
You guys know, Belantamab is an ADC. It works by many mechanisms, but blocks BCMA. It also,

00:03:43.740 --> 00:03:50.440
you know, basically gets internalized releases into the, into the cell and then causes apoptosis

00:03:50.440 --> 00:03:56.240
of the cell. And there may actually be some ADCC with this molecule. Single agent activity

00:03:56.240 --> 00:04:03.760
was about 30% in the DREAM-2 that led to the initial FDA approval. The interesting thing,

00:04:03.880 --> 00:04:12.640
the FDA made GSK do a dose finding phase two trial, right? So it was 2.5 versus 3.4. And lo and behold,

00:04:12.640 --> 00:04:19.260
there was no difference. So why not go with the less toxic, less toxic dose of 2.5 with less

00:04:19.260 --> 00:04:24.620
thrombocytopenia. And so that was brought forward. Now, as you know, the first phase three trial

00:04:24.620 --> 00:04:26.220
failed, right? And so that was brought forward. Now, as you know, the first phase three trial

00:04:26.220 --> 00:04:31.920
so it was taken off the market. One of the problems with Belantamab is it does cause a

00:04:31.920 --> 00:04:35.440
keratitis. I'm not going to say more about that because somebody on the panel is going to talk

00:04:35.440 --> 00:04:41.540
all about keratitis, but there's a bunch of DREAM studies and I have targeted Belantamab as the

00:04:41.540 --> 00:04:48.760
comeback kid in myeloma because of the DREAM-7 and the DREAM-8 studies. Now I'll just briefly

00:04:48.760 --> 00:04:55.840
mention DREAM-8 because somebody else is talking about Belapombex here. So the DREAM-8 study was

00:04:56.200 --> 00:05:01.660
done with Belapombex versus Belapombex. So it's kind of Bela versus Bortezomib as a head-to-head.

00:05:02.340 --> 00:05:11.120
And surprisingly, Bela won quite dramatically. And in fact, the PFS is probably going to be in

00:05:11.120 --> 00:05:16.160
the order of three plus years. For those of you that don't do myeloma in the audience,

00:05:17.000 --> 00:05:22.240
in the relapse refractory, one to three prior lines of therapy are top of the heap prior to

00:05:22.240 --> 00:05:26.180
CARS and bispecifics, prior to the data that you've seen over the last day or two.

00:05:26.180 --> 00:05:35.540
It has been ESA-KD and DERA-KD with 30 to 36 months PFS. This may eclipse it. This may actually

00:05:35.540 --> 00:05:41.740
be the top of the heap. And that's really pretty amazing for Belantamab, right? The medium PFS,

00:05:41.920 --> 00:05:47.420
obviously, in the control arm was a lot less. What about DREAM-7? DREAM-7 was head-to-head

00:05:47.420 --> 00:05:55.300
Belantamab versus DERA-tubemab. So it's BelaVD versus DERA-VD. And this was a standard relapse

00:05:56.160 --> 00:06:01.060
population. About a quarter of the patients had high-risk cytogenetics. And here we go,

00:06:01.180 --> 00:06:07.720
median PFS, 36 months versus 13 months. Bela crushed DERA-tubemab in a head-to-head,

00:06:07.900 --> 00:06:13.560
that's, you know, in combinations. That's amazing actually, right? And so this was approved by the

00:06:13.560 --> 00:06:19.580
FDA. I will point out that, you know, in the LEN, also in the LEN refractory, in the high-risk

00:06:19.580 --> 00:06:26.040
cytogenetics, this performed quite well. It's actually a very good combination. And there was

00:06:26.140 --> 00:06:32.920
a trend favoring BelaVD versus DERA-VD in overall survival. And that's really what led the FDA to

00:06:32.920 --> 00:06:40.460
approve this combination. Why the FDA didn't approve DERA-pomdex, we'll never know. If you

00:06:40.460 --> 00:06:49.400
listened to the ODAC meeting, you might know in the back of your mind. But not that it was bias or

00:06:49.400 --> 00:06:54.680
anything. I'm just saying, if you listened, you would have been okay. The one point I'm going to

00:06:56.120 --> 00:07:02.340
point is, Bela does induce some keratopathy, and then you have to lengthen out the dosing.

00:07:02.760 --> 00:07:07.340
And the dosing can go to every three months, can go to every four months. I used to do it back in

00:07:07.340 --> 00:07:12.160
the day, on-demand Bela. Somebody's light chains would go to 300, I'd give them a dose of Bela that

00:07:12.160 --> 00:07:16.740
goes back down to 50. I'd say, come back in three months, let's see. Three months, it's 50, I say,

00:07:16.860 --> 00:07:21.100
okay, come back three more months. And they get a dose every, twice a year, that was it.

00:07:21.680 --> 00:07:26.100
And I have some 80-year-olds that keep asking me, is that drug, that Bela drug, is that coming back

00:07:26.100 --> 00:07:31.340
out? Because I like that one. I only got a couple of doses a year. All right. The last thing I'll

00:07:31.340 --> 00:07:39.960
say is, at ASH, look at ASH 2025, Mari V. Mateos actually presented data on first relapse and

00:07:39.960 --> 00:07:45.000
functional high risk. And where the arrow is on the right, I want you to look at that. One prior

00:07:45.000 --> 00:07:52.800
line of therapy, DOR was 36 months for one line prior therapy and one prior line of therapy,

00:07:52.960 --> 00:07:56.080
functional high risk, 32 months. Those are really, really high risk.

00:07:56.080 --> 00:08:00.640
Really impressive data. And with that, I'll end and pass the baton.
